aws::graph::propositions: # Bell OH-58C Helicopter Hard Landing Incident in Omaha, Texas
Bell OH-58C helicopter with registration N911CC impacted terrain during a hard landing near Omaha, Texas.
The incident occurred on October 23, 2013, at approximately 0830 central daylight time.
The helicopter sustained substantial damage to the tail boom and main rotor blade(s).
The commercial pilot was uninjured in the incident.
The helicopter was registered to an individual.
The helicopter was operated by Reynolds Aviation.
The flight was conducted under 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 137 as an aerial application flight.
The flight was not operating on a flight plan.
Visual meteorological conditions prevailed for the flight.
The flight originated from Winnsboro, Texas, at 0700.
The flight was destined for Omaha, Texas.
The pilot was approaching to land with a load of chemical.
The left skid dug into high grass and loose dirt during landing.
The helicopter spun around after the skid dug into the terrain.
The main rotor contacted the tail boom during the spin.
The pilot reported no mechanical malfunction or failure with the helicopter.
The pilot held a Commercial certificate.
The pilot held a Flight engineer certificate.
The pilot was 49 years old.
The pilot had no Airplane Rating(s).
The pilot occupied the right seat.
The pilot held Helicopter aircraft rating(s).
The pilot's restraint use was unknown.
The pilot had no Instrument Rating(s).
No second pilot was present during the flight.
The pilot held Helicopter instructor rating(s).
No toxicology was performed on the pilot.
The pilot held a Class 2 Medical Certification with waivers/limitations.
The pilot's last Federal Aviation Administration medical examination was on May 14, 2013.
The pilot was an occupational pilot.
The pilot's last flight review or equivalent was on March 30, 2013.
The pilot had 9646 total flight hours in all aircraft.
The pilot had 5000 total flight hours in this make and model of helicopter.
The pilot had 211 flight hours in the last 90 days in all aircraft.
The pilot had 76 flight hours in the last 30 days in all aircraft.

# Factual Information

## History of Flight

| Approach | Collision with terr/obj (non-CFIT) |
| --- | --- |
| Landing-flare/touchdown | Hard landing (Defining event) |
| Landing-flare/touchdown | Collision with terr/obj (non-CFIT) |

On October 23, 2013, about 0830 central daylight time, a Bell OH-58C, N911CC, impacted terrain during a hard landing on a field near Omaha, Texas. The helicopter sustained substantial damage to the tail boom and main rotor blade(s). The commercial pilot was uninjured. The helicopter was registered to an individual and operated by Reynolds Aviation under 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 137 as an aerial application flight that was not operating on a flight plan. Visual meteorological conditions prevailed for the flight that originated from Winnsboro, Texas, at 0700 and was destined for Omaha, Texas.

The pilot stated that he was approaching to land with a load of chemical when the left skid dug into high grass and loose dirt. The helicopter spun around, and the main rotor contacted the tail boom.

The pilot reported that there was no mechanical malfunction/failure with the helicopter.
